Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:
(1) be able to program embedded micro-controllers for processing input/output digital and analog signals;
(2) be able to select the appropriate sensors and instrument a robot for processing the environmentâ€™s sensory data;
(3) be able to perform computer-aided designs (CAD) of mechanical components and select appropriate materials for a specific application;
(4) be able to select actuators and the motion driving mechanisms for a given engineering requirement;
(5) be able to implement simple control laws for conducting a specified motion task on the robot;
(6) be able to design, implement, conduct, and evaluate experiments.

Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:
(1) be able to read and understand mechanical drawings and CAD models of existing design;
(2) be proficient in using CAD software for product modelling, drafting, and analysis;
(3) have basic knowledge and exposure to product design and state-of-the-art manufacturing process;
(4) be able to carry out simple product design and 3-D prototyping in a team.

Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:
(1) be able to read and understand engineering drawings and CAD models of existing design;
(2) be able to have proficiency to use CAD software for product modelling, drafting, and analysis;
(3) be able to have basic knowledge of product design and manufacturing process;
(4) be able to carry out simple product design in a team.

Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:
(1) be able to understand the basic principles of engineering mechanics including both statics and dynamics;
(2) be able to interpret, simplify, and model given engineering problem situations;
(3) be able to work as individuals to conduct his/her engineering analysis through written descriptions or by oral presentation in a professional manner;
(4) be able to apply the fundamentals of mechanics to the preliminary design and evaluation of mechanical systems;
(5) be able to understand the mathematical models used for analysis and design;
(6) be able to apply the basic principles of particle and rigid body kinematics and dynamic analysis;
(7) be able to use different methods of approaching dynamics problems, such as work and energy, and impulse and momentum.

Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:
(1) apply the laws of thermodynamics to simple systems;
(2) formulate various types of energy transfer between systems or a system and its surroundings mathematically;
(3) solve simplified problems in thermodynamics by using appropriate tables and graphs;
(4) describe the fundamental principles behind various types of heat engines, refrigerators and heat pumps;
(5) model various types of heat engines, refrigerators and heat pumps and discuss their efficiencies.

Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:
(1) acquire basic mechanical, electronic and programming knowledge in the development of robots;
(2) be able to use motors, pneumatic actuator and sensors;
(3) be able to apply CAD drawing and manufacturing knowledge;
(4) have hands-on experience in robotic design and problem solving skills;
(5) solve robot design problems in a team environment and practicing of project management.

Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:
(1) examine the impact of engineering and technology on the society and the environment;
(2) recognize the contributions of engineers to the society;
(3) appreciate the design and innovation aspects of engineering profession;
(4) acquire the skills and tools to manage engineering projects;
(5) learn the communication and presentation skills for working in a team;
(6) understand the value of being an ethical engineer and a responsible citizen.

Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:

(1) have hands-on skills of engineering practice;
(2) understand the value of practical engineering skills and experiences.

Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:
(1) understand the fundamentals of prototype and product design;
(2) know how to create models of mechanical components using CAD softwares;
(3) demonstrate the capability of using appropriate manufacturing techniques;
(4) employ engineering and scientific principles to execute a design from concept to finished product;
(5) work as a team to complete a design project.

Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:
(1) deepen their understanding of topics related to mechanical and/or automation engineering, which may include mechanics, design, materials, fluid mechanics, thermodynamics, control, mechatronics and robotics;
(2) develop practical hands-on skills related to the topics of mechanical and automation engineering;
(3) using computer-aided tools to study and analyze mechanical systems;
(4) demonstrate effective engineering communication skills, including mathematical, verbal and visual means.

Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:
(1) analyze and interpret experimental results related to material stress-strain properties;
(2) apply equilibrium analysis to deformable structural members;
(3) apply suitable mathematical models to solve engineering problems in mechanics of materials;
(4) evaluate mechanical properties of materials and stresses in structural members in daily and engineering applications.

Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:
(1) understand the core technologies of manufacturing, their features, benefits and limitations;
(2) be skilled at communicating with appropriate media, including written reports and oral presentations on the core technologies of manufacturing;
(3) understand the important aspects of manufacturing by applying IT technologies;
(4) understand the influences of technological, environmental, social and cultural considerations on design and manufacturing decisions.

Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:
(1) use fluid mechanics terminology to describe fluid static and fluid flow phenomena appropriately;
(2) derive the governing equations for various types of fluid flow;
(3) identify deciding dimensionless parameters for various fluid flow phenomena, and design effective experiments based on these dimensionless parameters;
(4) solve fluid static problems by drawing free body diagrams and resolving forces;
(5) solve fluid flow problems by simplifying the governing equations of fluid motion appropriately, by using suitable empirical models, and by considering the conservation of energy.

Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:
(1) understand mechanical engineering design process, particularly machine design theory and methodology;
(2) develop critical thinking skills for design synthesis and analysis;
(3) obtain the core knowledge in engineering and mechanical design.

Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:
(1) be able to to qualitatively and quantitatively ascertain the advantages and disadvantages of closed loop system;
(2) be able to utilize various mathematical techniques in the modeling, stability analysis and performance evaluation of close loop system;
(3) understand the needed trade-off in a design process;
(4) understand the characteristics and analytical tools in different control design method;
(5) be able to use the computation tools Matlab for analysis and design;
(6) design a controller upon given a system and desired performance specifications;
(7) be able to conduct assigned system and control experiments to verify predicted phenomenon.

Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:
(1) solve the forward and inverse kinematics problems in robot manipulators;
(2) generate and analyse the Jacobian matrix, singularities and workspace in robot manipulators;
(3) perform trajectory generation and motion planning in robot manipulators;
(4) formulate the dynamics of robot manipulators;
(5) understand the use and the significance of sensors and actuators in robotics;
(6) apply fundamental knowledge of kinematics and motion planning on real robot hardware;
(7) appreciate the significance of robotics to the society.

Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:
(1) have a basic understanding of how objects are manipulated in a 3D space;
(2) understand the different types of curves and surfaces for modelling 3D objects;
(3) learn the basic concept and the different approaches for geometric and solid modelling;
(4) learn the popular techniques for visualizing 3D objects;
(5) to be capable of developing simple graphics applications.

Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:
(1) be able to develop a comprehensive understanding of the fundamental concepts and principles that underlie machine intelligence;
(2) be able to classify and differentiate between various categories of machine intelligence, including supervised learning, unsupervised learning, and intelligent searching;
(3) be able to acquire proficiency in implementing and applying key machine intelligence algorithms, such as linear regression, logistic regression, support vector machines, neural networks, clustering algorithms, and principal component analysis;
(4) be able to develop the ability to apply machine intelligence techniques to real-world problems and scenarios, demonstrating effective problem-solving skills;
(5) be able to evaluate the strengths and limitations of different machine intelligence approaches, fostering critical thinking and analytical skills.

Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:
(1) understand the design and implementation of specific computer-integrated manufacturing technologies addressed during the course;
(2) understand the strategic aspects and processes of new product design and manufacturing by applying computer integrated manufacturing technology;
(3) be able to skill at communicating with appropriate media, including mathematical graphical representations; (engineering drawings), written reports and oral presentations;
(4) be able to introduce the influences of technological, environmental, social and cultural considerations on design and manufacturing decisions;
(5) be able to identify the target markets and customers, strategic product features and benefits of the new design and manufacturing methods.

Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:
(1) be able to apply knowledge of engineering mathematics and science to finite element modelling and analysis;
(2) be able to design components using the finite element method to meet target need within constraint in the aspects of safety, manufacturability, sustainability, etc.;
(3) be able to formulate and solve mathematic equations for engineering problems using the finite element method;
(4) be able to use the computer / IT tools relevant to the finite element method along with understanding of their procedure and limitation.

Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:
(1) identify and explain the underlying heat transfer mechanisms of physical phenomena correctly;
(2) apply appropriate models to describe heat transfer problems mathematically;
(3) solve the formulated heat transfer problems to find the rate of heat transfer and temperature at specified locations.

Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:
(1) analyze the principles of actuators, sensors, as well as electronics and hardware components on the integration and application of mechatronic systems;
(2) design, build, program and troubleshoot mechatronic systems;
(3) competent to work as individuals and as members of a small team to communicate the results in a professional manner.

Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:
(1) be able to derive a state-space model for a given physical system;
(2) be able to perform stability analysis and computer simulation of time responses of the model;
(3) be able to perform various feedback controller design methods such as pole placement, observer design, feedforward design, internal model design, LQR method for fulfilling different design specifications;
(4) be able to analyze and design a discrete-time control system in both frequency domain and time domain.

Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:
(1) understand the basic components in the kernel of a VR system, and be able to specify three dimensional object shapes and movement of objects in mathematical terms;
(2) be able to use appropriate programming tools for developing virtual reality applications;
(3) be able to use standard input and output devices in virtual reality applications;
(4) be able to develop simple virtual reality applications.

Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:
(1) be able to formulate various engineering design problems into optimization problems;
(2) be able to solve various optimization problems including both linear and nonlinear programming, both analytic and numeric methods, and both constrained and unconstrained problems;
(3) be able to apply various optimization approaches to design problems encompassing mechanical engineering, electrical engineering, and manufacturing engineering.

Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:
(1) be able to use the principles of thermochemistry, fluid dynamics, and chemical kinetics to understand the basic combustion process;
(2) be able to calculate flame temperature for an idealized fuel-air mixture;
(3) be able to understand qualitatively how non-ideal factors affect flame temperature;
(4) be able to understand the difference between the basic types of internal combustion engines;
(5) be able to analyze an ideal engine cycle using thermodynamic diagrams and analyze the system performance of ideal Otto, Diesel and Brayton thermodynamic cycles;
(6) be able to analyze how CO, NO, unburned hydrocarbons and soot emissions are formed in engines and solutions to minimize them.

Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:
(1) be able to identify and have a basic understanding of the literature related to the project topic;
(2) be able to define and complete a project that utilizes results in the literature;
(3) be able to perform a critical review of the project;
(4) develop technical writing skills.

Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:
(1) be able to identify and have a basic understanding of the literature related to the project topic;
(2) be able to define and complete a project that utilizes results in the literature;
(3) be able to perform a critical review of the project;
(4) develop technical writing skills.

Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:
(1) explain the geometric algorithms used in existing CAD/CAM/CAE systems;
(2) be able to formulate a new geometric computing problem by mathematical equations;
(3) apply advanced mathematical formulation in their programming implementation;
(4) design new algorithms for achieve different functions in CAD/CAM/CAE systems;
(5) implement a geometric computing system with selected functions for design and manufacturing.

Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:
(1) identify peculiar nonlinear phenomena such as chaos, bifurcation, limit cycles, etc.;
(2) use classical nonlinear analysis tools such as the phase plane method and Poincare theory to study two dimensional systems;
(3) master advanced Lyaponov theory to analyze the stability property of both autonomous and non-autonomous nonlinear systems;
(4) select and apply some modern nonlinear control analysis and design methods such as backstepping method, feedback linearization method, and sliding mode method to design nonlinear control laws for nonlinear control systems.

Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:
(1) apply knowledge of engineering mathematics and science, to the subject of smart materials and structures;
(2) design devices and/or systems using smart materials;
(3) identify, formulate, and solve problems using smart materials technologies;
(4) use the modern engineering tools for the subject of smart materials and structures.

Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:
(1) identify state-of-the-art topics in robotics;
(2) generate new ideas for robot research and development;
(3) carry out project-based learning and research in robotics;
(4) understand impacts of robotics technology.

Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:
(1) understand basic quantum mechanics;
(2) understand principles of quantum control;
(3) understand principles of quantum information.

This course contributes to the following MAEG Programme Learning Outcomes:
(1) M1: An ability to apply knowledge of engineering sciences and mathematics to the discipline of mechanical and automation engineering;
(2) M3: An ability to design a system, component, or process to meet desired needs within social, environmental and technical constraints;
(3) M5: An ability to identify, formulate, and solve engineering problems;
(4) M10: An ability to recognize the need for and to engage in life-long learning;
(5) M11: An ability to use the techniques, skills and tools to practice in the mechanical and automation engineering discipline.

Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:
(1) understand fundamental concepts of nanotechnology and nanomaterials, including the scaling law, the surface science for nanomaterials, observation and characterization tools;
(2) understand the design principle and building blocks for nanodevices and systems;
(3) have an overall view of biomimetics and bio-inspired designs at small scales, and understand the fundamental challenges for locomotion and manipulation at micro-/nanoscales;
(4) understand material design principles of energy storage and conversion devices, solar energy harvesting devices and thermoelectric generators;
(5) propose technical solutions using nanomaterials and nanotechnology to tackle given technical challenge in biomedicine and energy applications.

