Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:
(1) explain the topological optimization algorithms used in existing CAD/CAE systems;
(2) apply mathematical formulations in their programming implementation for topological optimization;
(3) understand and apply different design rules for polymer and metal Additive Manufacturing;
(4) understand advantages and disadvantages of different Additive Manufacturing Technologies and corresponding design constraints.

Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:
1. Able to identify geometric functions of computer-aided design and manufacturing;
2. Able to apply engineering mathematics knowledge to conduct analysis for computer-aided design and manufacturing;
3. Competent to identify the influences of modern computing techniques on the development of advanced computer-aided design and manufacturing; and
4. Skilled at computer programming for computer-aided design and manufacturing.

Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:
1. Able to synthesize image and video observations in a camera from 3-D shape, motion, camera position, and camera settings;
2. Able to calibrate imaging system;
3. Understand the process of retrieving 3-D shapes and motions from image data using stereo vision, visual motion, and other vision cues; and
4. Able to relate typical engineering problems that require access to 3-D, to particular vision cues and the corresponding setups of the imaging system.

