1. apply knowledge of engineering mathematics and science, to the subject of smart materials and structures;
2. design devices and/or systems using smart materials;
3. identify, formulate, and solve problems using smart materials technologies; and
4. use the modern engineering tools for the subject of smart materials and structures.

Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:

1. To appreciate the development of the railway as one of the essential modes of transportation in the global setting;
2. To understand the modern railway transportation technologies and engineering considerations;
3. To appreciate train and railway systems design and technologies, and their impact to the environment;
4. To understand the railway development planning process and considerations; and
5. To understand railway operation and maintenance, safety concerns and risk management.

Upon the completion of the course, students should have achieved the following course learning outcomes:
1. A good understanding on the fundamental knowledge and latest development of the selected research area;
2. The ability to conduct research in the selected research area and adequate problem solving skills;
3. Good communication skills in terms of both written report and oral presentation.

At the end of the course of studies, a student should be able to
1. Have a good understanding and appreciate the characteristics of a Mechanical and Automation Engineering work environment, including employer expectation, management structure of a team, industrial standards and practices, trends and common issues in Mechanical and Automation Engineering, etc.;
2. Carry out basic duties in an Mechanical and Automation Engineering work environment;
3. Exhibit good etiquette in the workplace;
4. Work independently as well as in a team environment; and
5. Communicate effectively and efficiently with peers, supervisors and possibly also clients.
